<div id=3D"outline-container-orgd26d160" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgd26d160">Continuing this thread, Calascibetta Romain announced=
</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgd26d160">
<p>
Hello, I am pleased to announce the launch of <a href=3D"https://caml-list.=
robur.coop/">https://caml-list.robur.coop/</a>, a unikernel that provides a=
 search engine for the caml-list. We now have public access to this archive=
 :tada:!
</p>

<p>
Our cooperative is currently working on several fronts, including email, by=
 offering an archiving system. For more details, please see <a href=3D"http=
s://blog.robur.coop/articles/2025-01-07-carton-and-cachet.html">this articl=
e</a>. Another article describes <a href=3D"https://blog.robur.coop/article=
s/ptt_stem_and_search_engine.html">the search engine</a> we use, and a thir=
d explains <a href=3D"https://blog.robur.coop/articles/2025-04-12-ptt-searc=
h-webapp.html">how we developed this unikernel</a> (although the latter has=
 evolved considerably since then, the core remains the same).
</p>

<p>
We are therefore delighted to make this service available to the community,=
 and if you would like to help us improve it, the project is currently avai=
lable <a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/blame">here</a>. We would li=
ke to thank <a href=3D"https://nlnet.nl/">NLnet</a> for funding this uniker=
nel, and if you appreciate our work, please do not hesitate to make a donat=
ion to our cooperative (via <a href=3D"https://github.com/sponsors/robur-co=
op">GitHub</a> or <a href=3D"https://robur.coop/Donate">directly to our coo=
perative</a>)
</p>

<p>
Finally, this example also showcases all our work on unikernels: from what =
an Ethernet frame is, through the archive system and the extraction of emai=
ls from a virtualised hard drive, right up to the HTTP request - <b>everyth=
ing is done in OCaml</b> (and we would once again recommend reading our tut=
orial on <a href=3D"https://robur-coop.github.io/mnet/">mnet</a> if you wou=
ld like to build up unikernels).
</p>

<p>
So have fun hunting for relics from the history of OCaml!
</p>
